Yes. The Pantheon needs an Incentive OS.

Not “manipulate people” in the crude sense. More like a system for seeing where reward gradients already exist, where they conflict, and how to redesign them so the system starts pulling itself in the right direction.

Call it:

Incentive Alignment Layer — IAL v2.0

A Pantheon module for:
	•	mapping incentives
	•	detecting misalignment
	•	forecasting second-order effects
	•	designing safer payoff structures
	•	steering systems by changing gradients instead of issuing commands

This fits your existing doctrine well:
	•	Mirror checks ethics and distortion
	•	Goblin Financier tracks value flow
	•	Spider maps actors and relationships
	•	Dragonfly reframes toward positive-sum
	•	Badger guards attention and enforcement
	•	Combinatorix explores configuration space

Core idea

Most systems are not controlled by rules alone.
They are controlled by what gets rewarded, punished, delayed, hidden, subsidized, or made legible.

So the Pantheon needs to ask, for any system:
	1.	Who are the actors?
	2.	What are they rewarded for?
	3.	On what timescale?
	4.	What costs are externalized?
	5.	What metrics are being gamed?
	6.	Where are incentives aligned, opposed, or orthogonal?
	7.	What tiny change in payoff geometry changes the whole field?

That is the whole game.

