The 8-part Incentive Map

For each actor, build this card:

1. Actor

Who is making choices?

Examples:
	•	student
	•	university
	•	lender
	•	regulator
	•	consumer
	•	platform
	•	manager
	•	public

2. Objective function

What are they actually maximizing?

Not what they say. What behavior suggests.

Examples:
	•	short-term revenue
	•	prestige
	•	survival
	•	attention
	•	safety
	•	convenience
	•	reduced uncertainty
	•	career upside
	•	political optics

3. Reward channel

How do they feel the payoff?

Examples:
	•	money
	•	status
	•	time saved
	•	legal protection
	•	emotional relief
	•	social approval
	•	metrics / dashboards
	•	access / permissions

4. Penalty channel

What do they avoid?

Examples:
	•	shame
	•	loss
	•	public blame
	•	regulation
	•	friction
	•	uncertainty
	•	delay
	•	pain
	•	exclusion

5. Time horizon

When do they get rewarded or punished?

Examples:
	•	immediate
	•	quarterly
	•	election cycle
	•	career cycle
	•	lifetime
	•	intergenerational

A huge source of misalignment is short reward / long cost.

6. Visibility

Can the system see the true outcome?

If not, people game proxies.

Examples:
	•	test scores instead of learning
	•	admissions count instead of student outcomes
	•	engagement instead of well-being
	•	GDP instead of household resilience

7. Externalities

Who pays for the reward someone else gets?

This is where rot hides.

8. Exit / lock-in

How easily can actors leave, resist, or route around the system?

High lock-in means small misalignments become abusive.

⸻

The 6 canonical misalignment types

This should be a standard Pantheon classifier.

A. Proxy capture

The metric replaces the mission.

Example:
“maximize graduation rate” becomes lowering standards.

B. Externalized harm

One actor gains; another absorbs the cost.

Example:
easy lending, rising tuition, debt burden shifted to students.

C. Timescale inversion

Short-term gain produces long-term damage.

Example:
private equity cuts resilience for quarterly returns.

D. Information asymmetry

One side knows the game better than the other.

Example:
schools know expected outcomes better than teenagers do.

E. Lock-in asymmetry

One side can exit; the other cannot.

Example:
institution can change policy; debtor stays trapped.

F. Moral camouflage

System justifies extraction using a noble story.

Example:
“access,” “innovation,” “community,” “safety,” while value is being siphoned.

