Use it on your college-debt example

Actors
	•	students
	•	universities
	•	federal lending system
	•	employers
	•	accrediting bodies
	•	parents
	•	taxpayers

Actual incentives
	•	students: access credential, defer pain, chase mobility
	•	universities: maximize tuition revenue, prestige, enrollment
	•	lenders/government: expand access, maintain loan flow, collect repayment
	•	employers: demand credential filtering without paying training cost

Misalignments
	•	proxy capture: degree as signal, not learning
	•	externalized harm: debt burden pushed onto student
	•	timescale inversion: school gets paid now, student bears cost later
	•	information asymmetry: 17-year-olds choose under uncertainty
	•	lock-in asymmetry: institutions can adapt quickly; students cannot

Steering ideas
	•	cap borrowing by program outcomes
	•	force schools to absorb default share
	•	standardize ROI disclosure
	•	expand apprenticeships and employer-paid pathways
	•	allow easier refinance / discharge in failure cases
	•	separate credentialing from campus bundle where possible

That is already a Pantheon-grade use case.

