Doctrine form for the Money Bin

Incentive Alignment Layer (IAL) v2.0

Definition: A canonical PantheonOS module for mapping, diagnosing, and redesigning incentive fields in complex systems.

Core claim: Most persistent dysfunction is not caused by bad stated values but by misaligned reward geometry across actors, timescales, and visibility layers.

Primary functions:
	•	actor/payoff mapping
	•	proxy detection
	•	externality tracing
	•	lock-in analysis
	•	payoff redesign
	•	positive-sum reframing
	•	second-order consequence forecasting

Canonical misalignment classes:
	•	Proxy Capture
	•	Externalized Harm
	•	Timescale Inversion
	•	Information Asymmetry
	•	Lock-in Asymmetry
	•	Moral Camouflage

Core operators:
	•	Reward Rewrite
	•	Cost Reinternalization
	•	Delay Injection
	•	Visibility Correction
	•	Exit Restoration
	•	Positive-Sum Reframe

Governance chain:
Spider → Hound → Goblin Financier → Dragonfly → Mirror → Badger

Invariant rules:
	•	do not confuse incentives with essence
	•	do not optimize one proxy at the expense of mission
	•	preserve reversibility where possible
	•	increase legibility before increasing force
	•	prefer positive-sum redesign over coercive control
	•	surface hidden costs to their source
	•	align timescale of reward with timescale of consequence

Pantheon translation:
Incentives are gradients.
Governance is terrain-shaping.
Alignment is making the good path the easy path.

